explanation:
For a correct dead-code (MISRA) analysis we must know which operations in OS_TimerGetInfo can actually execute and produce observable effects. The following symbols are required and why:

- OS_CHECK_POINTER: macro that performs the initial pointer check; it may return early or produce side effects (e.g. logging). Its semantics determine whether the rest of the function can be executed.

- OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl: returns the object type for the current task ID. Required to determine whether the objtype check can cause the early return (i.e. whether the branch returning OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE can ever execute); if that branch is always/tacitly taken or never taken it affects whether subsequent code is live.

- OS_TaskGetId_Impl: supplies the task id to OS_ObjectIdToType_Impl. Its semantics (what id it returns in different contexts) are needed to decide the possible objtype values and reachability of the early-return branch.

- OS_OBJECT_TYPE_OS_TIMEBASE: the constant compared against objtype. Needed to interpret the objtype check and whether early return condition can be satisfied.

- OS_ERR_INCORRECT_OBJ_STATE: the error returned by the early-return branch. Knowing this value is not strictly required for reachability, but needed to know if returning here constitutes an observable effect (so removal would change behavior).

- OS_ObjectIdGetById: controls whether the main body (object table lookups and field reads/writes into timer_prop) executes. If this always fails (non-OS_SUCCESS), the block is dead; if it can succeed the block is live. Its semantics determine reachability of most of the function.

- OS_ObjectIdRelease: called when OS_ObjectIdGetById succeeds. Needed to know whether this call is required for observable state (resource/token release) and thus whether the call is live and not dead.

- OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: macro/function used to obtain record/timecb/timebase pointers from tokens/tables. Its definition drives whether the field accesses that follow are meaningful or optimized away; e.g., it may map tokens to pointers or indices and affect whether subsequent reads are live.

- OS_global_timecb_table, OS_timecb_table, OS_timebase_table: the object tables used by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET. Their types/contents determine whether lookups can succeed, and whether reading fields (name_entry, creator, interval_time, accuracy_usec) is meaningful — necessary to know if those reads are dead.

- OS_common_record_t: type of 'record' and its fields (name_entry, creator). Required to know whether copying record->name_entry and creator is an observable effect.

- OS_timecb_internal_record_t: type of 'timecb' and its fields (timebase_token, interval_time). Needed to determine whether timecb->interval_time read and timecb->timebase_token used for the next lookup are valid and thus whether subsequent operations are live.

- OS_timebase_internal_record_t: type of 'timebase' and its field (accuracy_usec). Required to determine whether copying accuracy to timer_prop has observable effect.

- OS_timer_prop_t: the output struct; its layout (name, creator, interval_time, accuracy) is necessary to decide whether the assignments/writes into timer_prop are observable and therefore not dead.

- OS_SUCCESS: value tested after OS_ObjectIdGetById. Needed to decide whether the if-block executes.

- osal_id_t, OS_object_token_t, osal_objtype_t: types used in the function signature and locals (timer_id, token, objtype). Their representations/semantics can affect how id/token/type conversions work and whether lookups succeed (reachability of code).

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: used by object-table/token translation paths (appears in the static call graph and may be utilized by OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET or related helpers). Its semantics affect whether tokens map to valid indices/pointers and therefore whether table accesses are live.

These symbols collectively determine (a) which branches and calls are reachable at runtime, and (b) whether their side-effects (returns, pointer reads/writes, token releases, writes into timer_prop, and any logging/printf from macros) are observable. Without their definitions/semantics you cannot conclude that any of the operations are dead (removable) or that they are required for correct program behaviour.
